<h2><a name="installation_considerations">4.0  Installation Considerations</a></h2>
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="rpm_support">4.1  RPM Support</a></h3>
<p>As of the time this readme was published, the
installation of Ingres requires RPM with a version in the
range 3.0.6 through 4.2.2, <b>except for RPM version
4.1</b>. If RPM 4.1 is installed, it must be upgraded to
version 4.1.1 or higher before you can install Ingres.
<p>RPM 4.1 fails to set environment variable
RPM_INSTALL_PREFIX.&nbsp;Attempting to install Ingres with
RPM 4.1 will lead to numerous "cannot find file" errors,
and a failed install.&nbsp;For further details of this RPM
bug, see <a href="http://bugzilla.redhat.com/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=75057" target="_blank">http://bugzilla.redhat.com/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=75057</a>.&nbsp;
<p>On RedHat Linux the rpmbuild package is required to
rename ingres packages using the iirpmrename utility. 
<p><b>Note</b>: When installing multiple Ingres RPM
packages, it is important that you install the "ingres2006"
(core) package before any other package.
<p>
<hr>
<h3>Upgrade Installs Using RPM</h3>
<p>These instructions allow you to upgrade ANY Ingres r3
release prior to 3.0.2(any.lnx/116) using RPM and avoid BUG
113652/Problem INGINS300 and BUG 114752. This document is
to be used in addition to the Ingres Migration Guide.
<p><b>Note:</b> For the purposes of this document build r3
3.0.1(int.lnx/103) has been used as the version of Ingres
being upgraded but the principle is the same for upgrading
all versions prior to r3 3.0.2(any.lnx/116)
<p><b>Upgrading Ingres</b> <b>r3</b> <b>3.0.1(int.lnx/103)
RPMs</b>
<ol>
<p><li>Make sure the Ingres instance you wish to upgrade is
completely shutdown and that you have taken a backup as
described in the Ingres Migration Guide.
<p><li>Obtain the list of Ingres r3 3.0.1(int.lnx/103) RPM
for the instance which is to be upgraded.
<pre>
rpm -qa | grep ca-ingres | grep 103
</pre>
<p>All of these packages must be upgraded at once. Any
attempt to perform an upgrade on any single or smaller
group of packages will fail.
<p><li>Login as root and CD to the directory containing the
RPM to be used to perform the upgrade. Make sure variable
II_CONFIG is not set.
<p><li>Run rpm -ivh to install the new RPMs over the
existing installation. If the installation was originally
installed using --prefix to change II_SYSTEM from the
default, then it MUST also be used for the upgrade.<br>
For default installation location:
<pre>
rpm -ivh --replacefile --replacepkgs \<br>
     &lt;complete list of RPM files to be install&gt;
</pre>
<p>Any other installation location:
<pre>
rpm -ivh --replacefiles --replacepkgs --prefix &lt;II_SYSTEM&gt; \<br>
     &lt;complete list of RPM files to be install&gt;
</pre>
<p><li>Remove the RPM package information for the old
installation (103) Check we can find the correct packages:
<pre>
rpm -qa | grep ca-ingres | grep 103
</pre>
<p>If the list is OK, then we can remove them:
<pre>
rpm -qa | grep ca-ingres | grep 103 | xargs rpm -e –justdb
</pre>
</ol>
<p><b>Note:</b> If you tried using rpm –Uvh instead
of the instructions above, binary and other installed files
(for example, iimerge) may be removed when rpm -Uvh is used
with --prefix to upgrade and installation. Should this
occur simply re-run the same command again using additional
flags --replacefiles & --replacepkgs and all the missing
files will be replaced. Any database or configuration files
will not be affected.    
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="documentation">4.2  Documentation</a></h3>
<p>Ingres documentation can be installed on Linux systems
by installing the documentation rpm file supplied with the
distribution.
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="mounting_the_cd_rom">4.3  Mounting the CD-ROM</a></h3>
<p>Most Linux distributions automatically mount the CD-ROM
as soon as it is placed in the drive. Running the command
"mount" returns an entry for /dev/cdrom if it has been
mounted.
<p>If it is not mounted, then it can be done manually. In
general, the CD-ROM should either be mounted to /mnt/cdrom
or /media/cdrom, depending on the distribution. The
following instructions are an example of how to mount the
CD-ROM on a RedHat Itanium Linux system:
<p>As root execute this command:
<pre>
mount /dev/cdrom /mnt/cdrom
</pre>
<p>For further information, see the <i>Getting Started</i>
guide.
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="installing_on_a_system_without_a_c_compiler">4.4  Installing on a System without a C Compiler</a></h3>
<p>This version of Ingres requires that the DBMS server
executables be re-linked so that utilities such as CKPDB
and ROLLFORWARDDB will function for users other than
"ingres". If a C compiler is present, the server is
re-linked at install time. If not, a warning is issued and
the install continues as usual. If users other than
"ingres" require the use of these utilities, the DBMS
server must be re-linked by hand with the following command:
<pre>
iilink –noudts
</pre>
<p>A C compiler must be installed for this command to
complete successfully.  
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="shared_library_path">4.5  Shared Library Path</a></h3>
<p>The library variable for Itanium Linux is
<b>LD_LIBRARY_PATH</b>.  
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="visual_tools">4.6  Visual Tools</a></h3>
<p>The Visual DBA suite is not included as part of the
Ingres 2006 Open Source for Itanium Linux. However, these
tools can be deployed on a Windows PC against Itanium Linux.
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="web_server_support">4.7  Web Server Support</a></h3>
Ingres for Itanium Linux supports the following web server:
<p><a href="http://www.apache.org/" target="_blank">Apache</a>
HTTP server 1.3
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="protocols_supported">4.8  Protocols Supported</a></h3>
<p>TCP/IP Native
<p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="raw_transaction_log_files_and_raw_database_locations_not_supported_on_linux">4.9  Raw Transaction Log Files and Raw Database Locations Not Supported on Linux</a></h3>
<p>Research has shown that raw transaction log files and
raw database locations on Linux do not provide performance
benefits. To simplify administration, a decision has been
made to not support this feature on Linux.
<p>
